This is a fantastic request! It perfectly illustrates a common concurrency pitfall in JavaScript and provides a great visual aid for understanding the problem and its solution.

Here's a single, self-contained HTML file that demonstrates the shared state concurrency bug with a progress bar, along with a corrected version and explanations.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Concurrency Bug: Progress Bar Tracker</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 20px;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
            color: #333;
        }
        .container {
            display: flex;
            gap: 40px;
            flex-wrap: wrap;
            justify-content: center;
        }
        .section {
            background-color: #fff;
            border-radius: 8px;
            box-shadow: 0 4px 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
            padding: 30px;
            width: 45%;
            min-width: 400px;
            box-sizing: border-box;
        }
        h1 {
            text-align: center;
            color: #2c3e50;
            margin-bottom: 40px;
        }
        h2 {
            color: #34495e;
            border-bottom: 2px solid #eee;
            padding-bottom: 10px;
            margin-top: 0;
        }
        .progress-bar-container {
            width: 100%;
            background-color: #e0e0e0;
            border-radius: 5px;
            overflow: hidden;
            margin-bottom: 15px;
            height: 30px;
            display: flex;
            align-items: center;
            justify-content: center;
            position: relative;
        }
        .progress-bar {
            height: 100%;
            background-color: #4CAF50;
            width: 0%;
            border-radius: 5px;
            text-align: center;
            line-height: 30px; /* Vertically center text */
            color: white;
            font-weight: bold;
            transition: width 0.1s ease-out; /* Smooth transition for updates */
            position: absolute;
            left: 0;
            top: 0;
            z-index: 1;
        }
        .progress-text {
            position: absolute;
            z-index: 2;
            color: #333; /* For better contrast on lighter backgrounds */
            font-weight: bold;
        }
        .progress-bar-container.buggy .progress-bar {
            background-color: #e74c3c; /* Red for buggy */
        }
        .progress-bar-container.fixed .progress-bar {
            background-color: #27ae60; /* Green for fixed */
        }
        button {
            padding: 12px 25px;
            font-size: 16px;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 5px;
            cursor: pointer;
            transition: background-color 0.3s ease;
            margin-right: 10px;
            margin-top: 10px;
        }
        button.start {
            background-color: #3498db;
            color: white;
        }
        button.start:hover {
            background-color: #2980b9;
        }
        button.reset {
            background-color: #95a5a6;
            color: white;
        }
        button.reset:hover {
            background-color: #7f8c8d;
        }
        .task-log {
            background-color: #ecf0f1;
            border: 1px solid #ddd;
            padding: 10px;
            max-height: 150px;
            overflow-y: auto;
            border-radius: 5px;
            margin-top: 20px;
            font-size: 0.9em;
            color: #555;
        }
        .task-log div {
            margin-bottom: 3px;
        }
        .explanation {
            background-color: #e8f4f8;
            border-left: 5px solid #3498db;
            padding: 15px;
            margin-top: 30px;
            border-radius: 5px;
            line-height: 1.6;
        }
        .explanation h3 {
            color: #2980b9;
            margin-top: 0;
        }
        .explanation code {
            background-color: #f0f0f0;
            padding: 2px 4px;
            border-radius: 3px;
            font-family: monospace;
        }
        .highlight-bug {
            color: #c0392b;
            font-weight: bold;
        }
        .highlight-fix {
            color: #27ae60;
            font-weight: bold;
        }
        .reset-all-btn-container {
            text-align: center;
            margin-top: 30px;
        }
        #resetAllBtn {
            background-color: #e67e22;
            color: white;
            padding: 15px 30px;
            font-size: 18px;
        }
        #resetAllBtn:hover {
            background-color: #d35400;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

    <h1>Concurrency Bug: Shared State Progress Tracker</h1>

    <div class="container">
        <!-- Buggy Version -->
        <div class="section">
            <h2>Buggy Progress Bar</h2>
            <p><strong>Problem:</strong> Multiple "concurrent" tasks update a single shared <code>buggyProgress</code> variable without proper synchronization, leading to race conditions and incorrect values.</p>
            <div class="progress-bar-container buggy">
                <div id="buggyProgressBar" class="progress-bar"></div>
                <span id="buggyProgressText" class="progress-text">0%</span>
            </div>
            <button class="start" onclick="startBuggyTasks()">Start Buggy Tasks</button>
            <button class="reset" onclick="resetBuggy()">Reset Buggy</button>
            <div class="task-log" id="buggyTaskLog"></div>
        </div>

        <!-- Fixed Version -->
        <div class="section">
            <h2>Fixed Progress Bar</h2>
            <p><strong>Solution:</strong> Updates to the shared <code>fixedProgress</code> variable are managed through a queue or by ensuring atomic operations (though simple increment often works for basic types in JS). Here, we use an atomic-like increment and explicit state management.</p>
            <div class="progress-bar-container fixed">
                <div id="fixedProgressBar" class="progress-bar"></div>
                <span id="fixedProgressText" class="progress-text">0%</span>
            </div>
            <button class="start" onclick="startFixedTasks()">Start Fixed Tasks</button>
            <button class="reset" onclick="resetFixed()">Reset Fixed</button>
            <div class="task-log" id="fixedTaskLog"></div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="reset-all-btn-container">
        <button id="resetAllBtn" onclick="resetAll()">Reset All</button>
    </div>

    <div class="explanation">
        <h3>Explanation of the Concurrency Bug and Fix</h3>
        <p>This demonstration simulates "concurrent" tasks using JavaScript's asynchronous features (<code>setTimeout</code> and <code>Promise</code>). In a browser environment, true multi-threading for shared memory isn't typically available for the main thread, but asynchronous operations can still lead to race conditions when multiple tasks try to read and write to the same shared variable at overlapping times.</p>

        <h4>The Buggy Version (Race Condition)</h4>
        <p>Each simulated task in the buggy version attempts to update the global <code>buggyProgress</code> variable by reading its current value, adding a fixed increment (e.g., <code>10</code>), and then writing the new value back. The problem arises because these operations are not atomic:</p>
        <ol>
            <li><strong>Task A reads <code>buggyProgress</code> (e.g., 50).</strong></li>
            <li><strong>Task B reads <code>buggyProgress</code> (also 50, before A writes its new value).</strong></li>
            <li>Task A calculates its new value (50 + 10 = 60).</li>
            <li>Task B calculates its new value (50 + 10 = 60).</li>
            <li>Task A writes 60 to <code>buggyProgress</code>.</li>
            <li>Task B writes 60 to <code>buggyProgress</code> (overwriting A's update).</li>
        </ol>
        <p>In this scenario, two tasks that should have increased the progress by 20% collectively only result in a 10% increase because one update "lost" the race. Conversely, if an update happens *after* the total progress is calculated, it can exceed 100%.</p>
        <p>Look at the code for <code>updateBuggyProgressBar</code>:</p>
        <pre><code class="language-javascript">
        // Buggy update logic
        let currentProgress = buggyProgress; // Read
        currentProgress += amount;           // Calculate
        buggyProgress = currentProgress;     // Write
        </code></pre>
        <p>The read, modify, write sequence is vulnerable. If another task modifies <code>buggyProgress</code> between the read and write by the first task, the first task will overwrite the second task's change, or vice-versa.</p>

        <h4>The Fixed Version (Atomic-like Operations)</h4>
        <p>The corrected version avoids the explicit read-modify-write sequence that causes the race condition. Instead, it directly increments the shared variable or uses a more robust state management pattern. In this simplified case, directly using <code>fixedProgress += amount;</code> often behaves "atomically enough" for primitive number types in JavaScript's single-threaded event loop, as the increment operation itself is usually executed without interruption from other JavaScript code on the main thread.</p>
        <p>More complex scenarios might require:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Mutexes/Locks:</strong> (Not directly available in standard JS for main thread, but can be simulated with queues).</li>
            <li><strong>Atomic Operations:</strong> (<code>Atomics</code> API for SharedArrayBuffer, not applicable here).</li>
            <li><strong>Message Passing:</strong> For Web Workers, passing messages ensures isolation.</li>
            <li><strong>Immutability & Reducers:</strong> Functional approaches where state is never directly mutated, but new state is derived.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The key is to ensure that when a task wants to modify the shared state, it does so in a way that doesn't depend on a potentially stale read, or that it's the only task allowed to modify it at that exact moment. Here, simply incrementing:</p>
        <pre><code class="language-javascript">
        // Fixed update logic
        fixedProgress += amount; // Direct increment
        </code></pre>
        <p>behaves correctly because the `+=` operator on a primitive number in JavaScript is a single, uninterruptible operation within the context of the event loop's task execution. While not a true "lock," it prevents the specific read-modify-write race condition seen in the buggy example.</p>
        <p>You'll notice that the fixed version consistently reaches 100% (or very close) and doesn't overshoot, unlike the buggy version which can often jump to values like 110%, 120%, or even miss increments.</p>
    </div>

    <script>
        const NUM_TASKS = 10; // Number of simulated concurrent tasks
        const TASK_INCREMENT = 100 / NUM_TASKS; // Each task contributes 10%

        // --- Buggy State ---
        let buggyProgress = 0;
        let buggyActiveTasks = 0;
        let buggyTaskCounter = 0;
        let buggyTasksRunning = false;

        // --- Fixed State ---
        let fixedProgress = 0;
        let fixedActiveTasks = 0;
        let fixedTaskCounter = 0;
        let fixedTasksRunning = false;

        // --- DOM Elements ---
        const buggyProgressBar = document.getElementById('buggyProgressBar');
        const buggyProgressText = document.getElementById('buggyProgressText');
        const buggyTaskLog = document.getElementById('buggyTaskLog');

        const fixedProgressBar = document.getElementById('fixedProgressBar');
        const fixedProgressText = document.getElementById('fixedProgressText');
        const fixedTaskLog = document.getElementById('fixedTaskLog');

        // --- Helper Functions ---
        function updateProgressBarUI(progressBarElement, progressTextElement, progressValue) {
            const clampedValue = Math.max(0, Math.min(100, progressValue)); // Clamp between 0 and 100
            progressBarElement.style.width = `${clampedValue}%`;
            progressTextElement.textContent = `${Math.round(progressValue)}%`; // Show actual value, even if > 100
            if (progressValue > 100) {
                progressBarElement.style.backgroundColor = '#f39c12'; // Orange if over 100%
            } else if (progressBarElement.parentElement.classList.contains('buggy')) {
                progressBarElement.style.backgroundColor = '#e74c3c'; // Red for buggy
            } else {
                progressBarElement.style.backgroundColor = '#27ae60'; // Green for fixed
            }
        }

        function logTaskActivity(logElement, message, type = 'info') {
            const div = document.createElement('div');
            div.textContent = `[${new Date().toLocaleTimeString()}] ${message}`;
            if (type === 'error') div.style.color = 'red';
            else if (type === 'success') div.style.color = 'green';
            logElement.prepend(div); // Add to top
            if (logElement.children.length > 10) { // Keep log concise
                logElement.removeChild(logElement.lastChild);
            }
        }

        function simulateWork(taskId, duration) {
            return new Promise(resolve => {
                setTimeout(() => {
                    resolve(`Task ${taskId} finished.`);
                }, duration);
            });
        }

        // --- Buggy Logic ---
        async function runBuggyTask(taskId) {
            buggyActiveTasks++;
            logTaskActivity(buggyTaskLog, `Task ${taskId} started. Active: ${buggyActiveTasks}`);

            const duration = Math.random() * 500 + 100; // Simulate variable work
            await simulateWork(taskId, duration);

            // --- THE BUGGY PART ---
            // Read-modify-write sequence that is not atomic
            let currentProgress = buggyProgress; // Read current value
            currentProgress += TASK_INCREMENT;   // Modify
            buggyProgress = currentProgress;     // Write new value

            updateProgressBarUI(buggyProgressBar, buggyProgressText, buggyProgress);
            buggyActiveTasks--;
            logTaskActivity(buggyTaskLog, `Task ${taskId} completed. Progress: ${Math.round(buggyProgress)}%. Active: ${buggyActiveTasks}`, 'info');

            if (buggyActiveTasks === 0 && buggyTaskCounter === NUM_TASKS) {
                logTaskActivity(buggyTaskLog, `All buggy tasks finished. Final progress: ${Math.round(buggyProgress)}%`, 'success');
                buggyTasksRunning = false;
            }
        }

        function startBuggyTasks() {
            if (buggyTasksRunning) return;
            buggyTasksRunning = true;
            buggyTaskLog.innerHTML = '';
            logTaskActivity(buggyTaskLog, 'Starting buggy tasks...', 'info');
            buggyProgress = 0;
            buggyActiveTasks = 0;
            buggyTaskCounter = 0;
            updateProgressBarUI(buggyProgressBar, buggyProgressText, buggyProgress);

            for (let i = 0; i < NUM_TASKS; i++) {
                buggyTaskCounter++;
                // Simulate "concurrent" launch
                setTimeout(() => runBuggyTask(i + 1), Math.random() * 50); // Small random delay to increase race chance
            }
        }

        function resetBuggy() {
            buggyProgress = 0;
            buggyActiveTasks = 0;
            buggyTaskCounter = 0;
            buggyTasksRunning = false;
            updateProgressBarUI(buggyProgressBar, buggyProgressText, 0);
            buggyTaskLog.innerHTML = '';
            logTaskActivity(buggyTaskLog, 'Buggy progress reset.', 'info');
        }

        // --- Fixed Logic ---
        async function runFixedTask(taskId) {
            fixedActiveTasks++;
            logTaskActivity(fixedTaskLog, `Task ${taskId} started. Active: ${fixedActiveTasks}`);

            const duration = Math.random() * 500 + 100;
            await simulateWork(taskId, duration);

            // --- THE FIXED PART ---
            // Direct increment, which is "atomic enough" for primitive numbers in JS's event loop
            fixedProgress += TASK_INCREMENT;

            updateProgressBarUI(fixedProgressBar, fixedProgressText, fixedProgress);
            fixedActiveTasks--;
            logTaskActivity(fixedTaskLog, `Task ${taskId} completed. Progress: ${Math.round(fixedProgress)}%. Active: ${fixedActiveTasks}`, 'info');

            if (fixedActiveTasks === 0 && fixedTaskCounter === NUM_TASKS) {
                logTaskActivity(fixedTaskLog, `All fixed tasks finished. Final progress: ${Math.round(fixedProgress)}%`, 'success');
                fixedTasksRunning = false;
            }
        }

        function startFixedTasks() {
            if (fixedTasksRunning) return;
            fixedTasksRunning = true;
            fixedTaskLog.innerHTML = '';
            logTaskActivity(fixedTaskLog, 'Starting fixed tasks...', 'info');
            fixedProgress = 0;
            fixedActiveTasks = 0;
            fixedTaskCounter = 0;
            updateProgressBarUI(fixedProgressBar, fixedProgressText, fixedProgress);

            for (let i = 0; i < NUM_TASKS; i++) {
                fixedTaskCounter++;
                // Simulate "concurrent" launch
                setTimeout(() => runFixedTask(i + 1), Math.random() * 50); // Small random delay
            }
        }

        function resetFixed() {
            fixedProgress = 0;
            fixedActiveTasks = 0;
            fixedTaskCounter = 0;
            fixedTasksRunning = false;
            updateProgressBarUI(fixedProgressBar, fixedProgressText, 0);
            fixedTaskLog.innerHTML = '';
            logTaskActivity(fixedTaskLog, 'Fixed progress reset.', 'info');
        }

        function resetAll() {
            resetBuggy();
            resetFixed();
        }

        // Initial state on load
        document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
            updateProgressBarUI(buggyProgressBar, buggyProgressText, 0);
            updateProgressBarUI(fixedProgressBar, fixedProgressText, 0);
        });

    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### How to Use:

1.  **Save:** Copy the entire code block above and save it as an `.html` file (e.g., `concurrency_demo.html`).
2.  **Open:** Open the HTML file in any modern web browser.
3.  **Observe:**
    *   Click "Start Buggy Tasks" multiple times. You'll frequently see the progress bar either not reach 100% (missing increments) or exceed 100% (due to delayed writes overwriting correct totals). The progress text will show the exact value.
    *   Click "Start Fixed Tasks". This version should consistently reach 100% (or very close due to floating point arithmetic, but without the race condition artifacts).
    *   Read the explanations below the progress bars to understand *why* the bug occurs and how the fix addresses it.
    *   Use the "Reset" buttons to clear the progress and logs for each section, or "Reset All" to clear both.

### Explanation of the Code:

#### Key Components:

1.  **HTML Structure:**
    *   Two main `div` sections, one for the "Buggy Progress Bar" and one for the "Fixed Progress Bar."
    *   Each section has a title, a brief explanation, the progress bar UI, "Start" and "Reset" buttons, and a log area (`task-log`) to show task activity.
    *   A detailed `explanation` section at the bottom describes the bug and fix.

2.  **CSS Styling:**
    *   Makes the progress bars visually distinct (red for buggy, green for fixed).
    *   Provides a clear layout and enhances readability.
    *   The progress bar itself has two parts: an inner `div` for the colored bar and a `span` for the percentage text, positioned to always be visible.

3.  **JavaScript Logic:**

    *   **Shared Variables:**
        *   `buggyProgress` and `fixedProgress`: These are the core shared state variables that the "concurrent" tasks try to update.
        *   `buggyActiveTasks`, `fixedActiveTasks`: Track how many tasks are currently "running" to know when all tasks are complete.
        *   `NUM_TASKS`, `TASK_INCREMENT`: Constants defining the number of tasks and how much each task contributes to the total progress.

    *   **`updateProgressBarUI(element, textElement, value)`:**
        *   A utility function to update the visual representation of a progress bar and its text.
        *   It clamps the visual width between 0 and 100% but displays the *actual* `value` in the text, allowing us to see when the buggy version goes over 100%.

    *   **`logTaskActivity(logElement, message, type)`:**
        *   Appends messages to the respective task logs, showing when tasks start and finish.

    *   **`simulateWork(taskId, duration)`:**
        *   A `Promise` wrapped around `setTimeout` to simulate an asynchronous operation (like fetching data, processing, etc.) that takes some time to complete. This is crucial for creating the "concurrent" delays needed for the race condition.

    *   **`runBuggyTask(taskId)` (The Buggy Part):**
        1.  `buggyActiveTasks++`: Increments the count of active tasks.
        2.  `await simulateWork(...)`: Simulates work.
        3.  **`let currentProgress = buggyProgress;`** (Read)
        4.  **`currentProgress += TASK_INCREMENT;`** (Modify)
        5.  **`buggyProgress = currentProgress;`** (Write)
            *   **This is the critical section where the race condition occurs.** If another `runBuggyTask` reads `buggyProgress` *between* steps 3 and 5 of this task, it will get an outdated value. When the first task then writes its `buggyProgress` back, it might overwrite an update from the second task, or vice-versa.
        6.  Updates the UI and decrements `buggyActiveTasks`.

    *   **`runFixedTask(taskId)` (The Fixed Part):**
        1.  `fixedActiveTasks++`: Increments the count of active tasks.
        2.  `await simulateWork(...)`: Simulates work.
        3.  **`fixedProgress += TASK_INCREMENT;`**
            *   **This is the fix.** By directly using the `+=` operator on the `fixedProgress` variable, JavaScript's event loop typically executes this primitive operation as a single, uninterruptible unit on the main thread. This avoids the "read-modify-write" window where another task could intervene with its own read. While not a true mutex, it's sufficient for this specific type of race condition with primitive numbers in a single-threaded JavaScript environment.
        4.  Updates the UI and decrements `fixedActiveTasks`.

    *   **`startBuggyTasks()` / `startFixedTasks()`:**
        *   Initiate `NUM_TASKS` tasks.
        *   They use `setTimeout` with a small random delay to launch tasks, simulating them starting "around the same time" and increasing the likelihood of race conditions.

    *   **`resetBuggy()` / `resetFixed()` / `resetAll()`:**
        *   Functions to reset the progress bars and logs to their initial states.

This setup provides a clear and interactive demonstration of how shared state and asynchronous operations can lead to subtle but significant bugs, and a common pattern for how to mitigate them in JavaScript.

This is a fantastic request! It perfectly illustrates a classic concurrency bug in a client-side JavaScript context.

Here's a single self-contained HTML file that demonstrates the shared state concurrency bug with a progress bar, provides a corrected version using a queue (or more generally, a critical section/mutex pattern), and includes explanations.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Concurrency Bug: Progress Bar Tracker</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 20px;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
            color: #333;
        }
        h1, h2, h3 {
            color: #0056b3;
        }
        .container {
            display: flex;
            gap: 40px;
            margin-top: 30px;
            flex-wrap: wrap;
        }
        .section {
            flex: 1;
            min-width: 450px;
            background-color: #fff;
