            color: red;
            font-weight: bold;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

    <h1>Concurrency Bug: Progress Bar Tracker</h1>
    <p>This page demonstrates a common shared-state concurrency bug using a progress bar. Observe how the "Buggy Version" often shows incorrect percentages or exceeds 100% when multiple tasks try to update the progress simultaneously.</p>

    <div class="container">
        <!-- Buggy Version -->
        <div class="section">
            <h2>Buggy Version (Shared State without Protection)</h2>
            <p><strong>Problem:</strong> Multiple "tasks" try to read and write to <code>buggyProgressPercentage</code> directly and concurrently, leading to race conditions.</p>

            <div class="progress-container">
                <div id="buggyProgressBar" class="progress-bar">0%</div>
            </div>
            <div class="controls">
                <button id="startBuggyBtn">Start Buggy Tasks</button>
                <button id="resetBuggyBtn" disabled>Reset Buggy</button>
            </div>
            <div class="log" id="buggyLog"></div>
        </div>

        <!-- Corrected Version -->
        <div class="section">
            <h2>Corrected Version (Using a Queue/Critical Section)</h2>
            <p><strong>Solution:</strong> Updates to <code>correctedProgressPercentage</code> are funneled through a processing queue, ensuring only one update happens at a time.</p>

            <div class="progress-container">
                <div id="correctedProgressBar" class="progress-bar">0%</div>
            </div>
            <div class="controls">
                <button id="startCorrectedBtn">Start Corrected Tasks</button>
                <button id="resetCorrectedBtn" disabled>Reset Corrected</button>
            </div>
            <div class="log" id="correctedLog"></div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="explanation">
        <h3>Explanation of the Concurrency Bug</h3>
        <p>In JavaScript, even though it's single-threaded for execution, asynchronous operations (like <code>setTimeout</code> or Promises) can lead to apparent concurrency problems when dealing with shared state. The "buggy" version demonstrates a classic <strong style="color:red;">race condition</strong>.</p>
        <p>Imagine the following sequence for two tasks, A and B, both trying to add 10% to the progress:</p>
        <ol>
            <li>Current progress is 50%.</li>
            <li><strong>Task A:</strong> Reads current progress (50%).</li>
            <li><strong>Task B:</strong> Reads current progress (50%).</li>
            <li><strong>Task A:</strong> Calculates new progress (50 + 10 = 60%).</li>
            <li><strong>Task B:</strong> Calculates new progress (50 + 10 = 60%).</li>
            <li><strong>Task A:</strong> Writes new progress (sets it to 60%).</li>
            <li><strong>Task B:</strong> Writes new progress (sets it to 60%).</li>
