            <li>A separate function (<code>processQueue</code>) checks if there's anything in the queue and if it's currently processing.</li>
            <li>If the queue has items and nothing is being processed, it takes the first item, applies the update, and then marks itself as done, allowing the next item to be processed.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>This pattern effectively creates a <strong style="color:green;">critical section</strong> for the shared resource (the progress percentage), ensuring that only one "thread of execution" (or asynchronous operation, in JS terms) can modify it at any given moment. This prevents race conditions and ensures data integrity.</p>
        <p>While JavaScript's event loop prevents true multi-threading data corruption, the logical inconsistency (like the lost update or exceeding 100%) is a very real and common bug that this pattern addresses.</p>
