    <h1>Shared State Concurrency Bug Demonstration</h1>

    <div class="explanation">
        <h3>The Problem: Race Conditions with Shared State</h3>
        <p>
            In concurrent programming, a <span class="bug-highlight">race condition</span> occurs when multiple threads or tasks attempt to access and modify the same shared resource (like a variable) without proper synchronization. The final outcome depends on the non-deterministic order in which these tasks execute.
        </p>
        <p>
            In this example, both progress bars are updated by multiple "tasks" (simulated by <code>setTimeout</code> and <code>Promise</code>). Each task increments a global <code>progressPercentage</code> variable.
        </p>
        <p>
            The bug arises because the operation <code>progressPercentage = progressPercentage + amount;</code> is not atomic. It involves three steps:
            <ol>
                <li>Read the current value of <code>progressPercentage</code>.</li>
                <li>Add <code>amount</code> to it.</li>
                <li>Write the new value back to <code>progressPercentage</code>.</li>
            </ol>
            If two tasks read the same old value before either writes its new value, one update will effectively be lost. This leads to the progress bar showing incorrect values, skipping percentages, or even exceeding 100% if the intermediate reads/writes get interleaved in a specific way.
        </p>
        <h3>The Fix: Protecting Shared State</h3>
        <p>
            The simplest way to fix this in JavaScript (which is single-threaded for its main execution loop) is to ensure that updates to the shared variable are performed sequentially or in a controlled manner.
        </p>
        <p>
            For UI updates and state management, a common pattern is to use a <span class="fix-highlight">queue of updates</span> or to ensure that all modifications to a shared state variable happen through a single, controlled function that processes updates one by one. In the "Corrected" example, we use a <span class="fix-highlight">promise chain</span> to ensure that each update operation effectively waits for the previous one to complete before reading and updating the shared state. This serializes the updates, eliminating the race condition.
        </p>
        <p>
            Another common approach in more complex scenarios (e.g., Node.js workers, Web Workers, or other languages) is to use <span class="fix-highlight">locks, mutexes, or atomic operations</span> to protect the critical section of code that modifies the shared resource.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="container">
        <div class="panel">
            <h2>Buggy Implementation</h2>
            <p>
